{
    "analysis": "From the prior file summaries: metric/trace/log data cover 2024-01-19T18:35:00 to 18:59:00 UTC which overlaps the incident window. error_logs.csv contains 45 rows from 18:47:43 to 18:58:29 UTC and all error messages are 'failed to retrieve ads' coming from the frontend with gRPC errors (DeadlineExceeded / Unavailable) occurring around 18:47–18:48 UTC. Metric KPIs available include cpu, diskio, latency-50, latency-90, mem, socket, workload, error; trace features include many trace.from_*/trace.to_* entries (including recommendationservice-related traces). Given the error logs indicate frontend failing to retrieve ads, likely downstream ad-related services (adservice or recommendationservice/productcatalogservice) are implicated. However, per the diagnosis rules the root-cause component must be selected from the provided candidate list (checkoutservice, currencyservice, emailservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice). The next step is to perform metric anomaly detection focused on those candidate services: compute global thresholds (P95) per component-KPI using the full available series, then filter metric points to the incident window and report counts, how many exceed P95, earliest exceedance timestamp (if any), and max value within the window — this will narrow down which service(s)/KPI(s) show anomalies correlated with the error timeframe.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, for each candidate service in [checkoutservice, currencyservice, emailservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice]: 1) compute the global P95 threshold for each kpi_name using the full available metric series for that (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair (do NOT filter by incident window when computing P95); 2) then filter metric rows to the incident window 2024-01-19 18:32:37 to 2024-01-19 19:02:37 UTC and for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) report a single summary row containing: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_P95, total_points_in_window, points_above_P95_in_window, earliest_timestamp_above_P95_in_window (ISO UTC) or null if none, and max_value_in_window. Limit output to at most 100 rows (should be small). Return the result as a compact table."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous metric-anomaly summary: global P95 thresholds were computed per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using full series, and metric points within the incident window were compared against those thresholds. Several KPI series for checkoutservice and recommendationservice had points above their global P95 within the window (each showing 2 points above P95 in the sample). error_logs.csv shows multiple frontend error messages \"failed to retrieve ads\" (gRPC DeadlineExceeded / Unavailable) concentrated around 2024-01-19T18:47–18:48Z. That suggests a client-facing failure (frontend) calling downstream services for ads or recommendations; adservice itself is not in the allowed candidate list, so among the provided candidates the anomalies in recommendationservice (and possibly productcatalogservice) are suspicious. However, we must follow the fault-identification rules: identify consecutive anomalous sub-series (faults), ignore isolated spikes, and assess severity (breach ratio). The next step is to detect consecutive anomaly sequences per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) inside the incident window using the previously computed global P95 thresholds, and report sequence counts, longest sequence length, earliest sequence start, and max breach ratio (max_value/global_P95) so we can identify true faults and earliest occurrence times for root-cause localization.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, for the candidate services [checkoutservice, currencyservice, emailservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice]: 1) (Re)compute the global P95 for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using the full available metric series for that pair. 2) Filter metric rows to the incident window 2024-01-19 18:32:37 to 2024-01-19 19:02:37 UTC. 3) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name), detect all consecutive anomaly sequences where value > global_P95 (consecutive means adjacent timestamps in the filtered series). For each pair output a compact summary row with: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_P95, number_of_anomalous_sequences_in_window, longest_sequence_length, earliest_sequence_start_in_window (ISO UTC) or null, max_value_in_window, max_breach_ratio = max_value_in_window/global_P95. 4) Return only rows where number_of_anomalous_sequences_in_window > 0, sorted by earliest_sequence_start ascending, limit to 20 rows."
}

{
    "analysis": "Metric analysis completed: global P95 thresholds were computed and metrics within the incident window were checked. Results show multiple candidate services (checkoutservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice, currencyservice, emailservice) had isolated single-minute spikes just above their P95s. Most breaches are very small (~1–3% above P95) except currencyservice memory (~9% above P95). Error logs show frontend experienced repeated \"failed to retrieve ads\" gRPC errors (DeadlineExceeded / Unavailable) concentrated around 2024-01-19T18:47–18:48Z. Given the frontend errors are about retrieving ads/recommendations, traces to/from recommendationservice and productcatalogservice are the most relevant to determine the downstream faulty service. The next step is trace analysis to look for increased latency or error_rate (above global thresholds) or traffic drops (row_count below low-percentile) for trace entries involving recommendationservice/productcatalogservice and frontend around the error time to localize the downstream faulty service.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv, select rows where trace_name or cmdb_id contains any of ['recommendationservice','productcatalogservice','frontend','frontendservice']. For each distinct (cmdb_id, trace_name) pair: 1) compute the global P95 using the full available series for that pair (do NOT restrict to the incident window when computing P95). 2) Filter rows to the incident window 2024-01-19 18:32:37 → 2024-01-19 19:02:37 UTC. 3) For each pair report: cmdb_id, trace_name, global_P95, total_points_in_window, points_above_P95_in_window, earliest_timestamp_above_P95_in_window (ISO UTC or null), max_value_in_window. 4) Additionally, for trace_name values that end with 'row_count' compute global P5 (from full series) and report points_below_P5_in_window and earliest_timestamp_below_P5_in_window (ISO UTC) instead of points_above. Return at most 50 rows sorted by earliest anomaly time (earliest above/below) ascending. Keep output compact."
}

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis so far narrowed candidates: multiple short trace anomalies exist across productcatalogservice, recommendationservice, and frontendservice. Notably, trace.to_recommendationservice.row_count (root) had two points below its global P5 at 2024-01-19T18:35:00+00:00, and several trace pairs involving frontend→* and *←frontend showed P95 breaches around 18:37 and a cluster of trace-duration/error-rate anomalies around 18:50. Metric anomalies across candidate services are mostly isolated single-minute spikes with small breach ratios, except currencyservice memory at ~18:52 which is outside the main frontend error cluster. Error logs from error_logs.csv show frontend gRPC failures (“failed to retrieve ads” with DeadlineExceeded / Unavailable) concentrated at ~18:47–18:48 UTC. To localize the root cause we need to directly inspect trace events involving recommendationservice (and the frontend→recommendation call) during the incident window to see if there are error_rate increases, traffic drops, or latency spikes aligned with the frontend errors. This will help decide whether recommendationservice (or productcatalogservice) is the downstream faulty service causing the frontend \"failed to retrieve ads\" messages.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From trace.csv, extract all rows within 2024-01-19 18:32:37 → 2024-01-19 19:02:37 UTC where trace_name contains the substring 'recommendation' (case-sensitive). Return a compact table with columns: timestamp (ISO UTC), cmdb_id, trace_name, value. Sort by timestamp ascending and limit to 100 rows."
}

{
    "analysis": "Trace extraction for 'recommendation' returned 100 rows spanning 2024-01-19T18:35:00 → 2024-01-19T18:39:00 UTC, showing normal (near-zero) error_rate and varying row_count; however, frontend error logs indicating \"failed to retrieve ads\" cluster at ~2024-01-19T18:47–18:48 UTC. There is a timing mismatch: the recommendation-related traces we inspected so far are earlier (18:35–18:39) than the frontend errors (18:47–18:48). Metric anomalies in candidate services are mostly isolated single-minute small breaches, except currencyservice memory (~18:52) which is later and more severe. To localize the root cause we must compare exact frontend error timestamps against trace activity at those same times (18:47–18:48) and look for trace-level latency/error_rate/row_count anomalies involving recommendationservice or productcatalogservice at or immediately before the frontend error events. First, confirm the precise error log events within the incident window so we can align trace timestamps.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load error_logs.csv and filter rows to the incident window 2024-01-19 18:32:37 → 2024-01-19 19:02:37 UTC. Return a compact table sorted by timestamp ascending with columns: timestamp (ISO UTC), cmdb_id, message. Limit to 200 rows. Also include a short aggregate: total error rows in the window and counts grouped by message (top 10) and by cmdb_id (top 10)."
}

Review summary: frontend began reporting repeated gRPC timeouts/unavailability when retrieving ads at 2024-01-19T18:47:43 UTC. Trace data shows large request bursts to the recommendation (ads) path around 18:46–18:48, while downstream services did not show internal error logs. The most consistent explanation is a transient overload of the recommendation service causing frontend deadlines to be hit (manifesting as gRPC DeadlineExceeded/Unavailable). From the provided candidate reasons, this maps to high CPU usage on recommendationservice.

